1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. e3 Qa5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Qd2 Bb4 9. Rc1 h6 10. Bh4 c5 {The main line. Surprisingly this position had
never occurred in my games before.} (10... O-O {0-1 L'Ami,E (2541)-Gurevich,M 
(2652)/Germany 2006/CBM 112/[Gurevich,M] (63) However I'd based my home
preparation on Kramnik's nice win in the following game. 1-0 Kramnik,V (2729)
-Bruzon Bautista,L (2652)/Turin 2006/CBM 113 (32)}) 11. a3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 b6 13.
Ne5 $6 {An extremely rare move, which shouldn't promise much, but can serve as
a surprise weapon. White changes pawn structure in order to unbalance the
position.} ({White has also tried other options and three of them are at least
not worse than the text.} 13. Bd3 {1/2-1/2 Ruck,R (2546)-Dreev,A (2698)/Saint
Vincent 2005/CBM 110/[Babula,V] (32).}) (13. c4 {1-0 Grischuk,A (2710)-Dreev,A
(2704)/Poikovsky 2005/CBM 106/[Erenburg] (35)}) (13. Bg3 {0-1 Gligoric,S (2481)
-Blagojevic,D (2486)/Herceg Novi 2001/CBM 083/[Tsesarsky] (34)}) (13. e4 {1/
2-1/2 Atalik,S (2593)-Nogueiras,J (2540)/Havana 1999/CBM 071/[Tsesarsky] (63)})
13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 g5 15. Bg3 {Only this natural retreat turns out to be a
novelty.} ({In the only preceding game White played} 15. e4 Ne7 (15... Nxc3 $5
16. Bg3 Nxe4 17. Qxa5 bxa5 18. f3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 $11) 16. Rd1 O-O 17. Bg3 Bb7
$132 {0-1 Sherbakov,R (2559)-Goloshchapov,A (2446)/Ekaterinburg 1999/CBM 075 
(58)  with a double edged position.}) 15... Bb7 16. e4 Ne7 17. h4 $5 ({The
solid} 17. f3 $5 {was also possible.[%cal Gh2h4]}) 17... Bxe4 {Eliminating an
important central pawn.} (17... g4 $5) 18. hxg5 h5 {I took a long thought here.
It's clear that White wants to prevent long castling. On the other hand the
a3-pawn is hanging. Suddenly a surprising idea came to my mind and I played}
19. Qb2 $5 ({It's not clear what White achieves after} 19. f3 Bc6) 19... O-O-O
$6 {Missing White's idea.} (19... Bc6 $1 {Preparing to castle long was better.}
) 20. Qb4 $1 {The point of the previous move.} Qxb4 (20... cxb4 21. cxb4+ $14)
21. cxb4 Bd3 $5 {An interesting pawn sacrifice. Black's idea is to exchange
the light-squared bishop, to meet bxc5 with b5 and then to block the c-pawn on
c6, while the knight will dominate over the dark-squared bishop.} (21... Ng6 $5
{[%cal Gh5h4]}) 22. bxc5 b5 {[%cal Gc8c7,Gc7c6]} 23. Rh4 $1 {The rook enters
the game.[%cal Ga3a4]} Bxf1 24. Kxf1 Kb7 $6 {[%cal Gb7c6]} (24... Nf5 $1 25.
Rb4 Nxg3+ 26. fxg3 a6 27. a4 $1 Rhg8 28. axb5 axb5 29. Rxb5 Rd5 $1 $11) ({In
the event of} 24... Kc7 25. Rf4 {with the idea} Nf5 $2 (25... Rhf8 $5) 26. Rxf5
exf5 27. e6+ Kc6 28. exf7 $18 {and White's pawns decide the game.}) 25. a4 $1 {
Preparing the following beautiful combination.} a6 26. Rf4 $1 Nf5 $6 (26... Rh7
$14 {was a better defence.}) 27. c6+ $1 {Not allowing him to block the c-pawn.}
Kb6 28. a5+ $1 Kxa5 $2 {The losing move.} (28... Ka7 {was necessary, but White
retains a better position after} 29. Bh2 $14) 29. Rxf5 $1 exf5 30. e6 $1 fxe6 (
{The game can't be saved after} 30... Rdf8 31. Bc7+ Ka4 32. Be5 $1 Rhg8 33. Bd6
fxe6 34. Ra1+ Kb3 35. Bxf8 Rxf8 36. g6 Rc8 37. g7 $18 {and White wins.}) 31.
Bc7+ Ka4 ({or} 31... Kb4 32. Bxd8 Rxd8 33. g6 Rc8 (33... Ka5 34. c7 Rc8 35. g7
{[%cal Gc1d1,Gd1d8]} b4 (35... Kb6 36. Rd1 $1 $18) 36. Rd1 b3 37. Ke2 $1 h4 (
37... b2 38. Rb1 $1) 38. g8=Q Rxg8 39. Rd8 b2 40. c8=Q b1=Q 41. Qc5+ Ka4 42.
Rd4+ $18) (33... a5 34. c7 Rc8 35. Rb1+ {-33...Rc8}) (33... Ka3 34. c7 Rc8 35.
g7 b4 36. Ra1+ $1 Kb2 37. Rd1 $18) (33... Ka4 34. Ra1+ $1 Kb3 35. c7 Rc8 36. g7
b4 37. Rd1 $18) 34. g7 a5 (34... Ka5 35. c7 b4 36. Ke2 b3 37. Rd1 h4 38. Kf3 $1
f4 (38... e5 39. Rd5+ $1 Ka4 40. Rd8 b2 41. g8=Q b1=Q 42. Qc4+ Ka5 43. Rd5+ Kb6
44. Rd6+ Kb7 45. Qc6+ Ka7 46. Qxa6#) 39. Rd8 (39. Rd2 $5) 39... b2 40. Rxc8
b1=Q 41. g8=Q $18 {and the king escapes the checks.}) 35. Rb1+ $18 {31...Ka4.})
32. Ra1+ (32. Bxd8 Rxd8 33. Ra1+ {transposes to 32.Ra1.}) 32... Kb4 (32... Kb3
33. Bxd8 Rxd8 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gc8c7]} 34. g6 $1 {Preventing the Rc8-c7 idea.} b4
35. c7 Rc8 36. g7 Kc2 (36... Kc4 37. Rd1 b3 38. g8=Q $1 Rxg8 39. Rd8 $18) 37.
Ra2+ $1 Kc1 (37... Kc3 38. Rxa6 b3 39. Rc6+ Kd2 40. g8=Q Rxg8 41. Rd6+ Kc2 42.
Rd8 $18) 38. Ke2 $1 b3 39. Rd2 b2 40. g8=Q $1 Rxg8 41. Rd8 b1=Q 42. c8=Q+ Kb2
43. Rd2+ $18) 33. Rxa6 $4 $138 {After missing a decisive idea of g8Q with the
following Rd8 I decided to try playing with a bishop and two passed pawns vs a
rook. A typical time trouble idea.} ({Meanwhile} 33. Bxd8 $1 {leads to a
forced win.} Rxd8 34. g6 $1 (34. Rxa6 $2 Kc5 35. c7 Rc8 36. Rxe6 Rxc7 37. Re5+
Kc4 38. Rxf5 b4 39. Ke2 b3 40. Kd2 Kb4 41. g6 b2 42. Rf8 Kb3 43. Rb8+ Ka2 44.
Ra8+ $11) 34... a5 (34... Kc5 35. c7 Rc8 36. g7 b4 37. Rd1 b3 38. g8=Q $1 Rxg8
39. Rd8 $18) 35. Rb1+ $1 {An important intermediate check.} Ka4 (35... Kc5 36.
c7 Rc8 37. g7 b4 38. Rd1 b3 39. g8=Q $1 {This is the idea I missed in my
calculations.} Rxg8 40. Rd8 $18) (35... Kc3 36. g7 Rc8 37. c7 a4 38. Rd1 a3 39.
g8=Q $1 Rxg8 40. Rd8 $18) 36. c7 Rc8 37. g7 b4 38. Ra1+ $1 {Another strong
intermediate check. Now Black is forced either to go to b5 and then the king
will be on the same line with the future queen on b1 or to b3 where the king
prevents advance of its own b-pawn.} Kb5 (38... Kb3 39. Rd1 $1 $18) 39. Rd1 {
[%cal Gd1d8]} b3 40. Ke2 $3 $18 {The key-move. White takes his king away from
the first rank and prepares Rd8. At the same time Black can't advance the
b-pawn as it will be immediately lost.} Ka4 {Moving the king away from the
b-file.} (40... b2 41. Rb1 $1 Kc6 42. Rxb2 $18 {[%cal Gb2b8]}) (40... a4 41.
Rd8 b2 42. Rxc8 $18 {[%cal Gc8b8]}) 41. Rd4+ $1 {Once again Black has to make
an unpleasant choice: either the king goes to the b-file and loses the queen
after Rd8-c8-b8+ or to a3 where it gets under Qg3+.} Ka3 (41... Kb5 42. Rd8 b2
43. Rxc8 b1=Q 44. Rb8+ $18) 42. Rd8 b2 43. g8=Q b1=Q 44. Qg3+ $1 Ka4 (44... Ka2
45. Rd2+ $18) 45. Qf4+ Kb5 46. Qe5+ $18 {and with the centralized queen White
can capture the rook. This would crown White's combination started with 25.a4!}
) (33. Ba5+ $5 {is also enough for a win.} Kc4 (33... Kb3 34. Bxd8 Rxd8 {
transposes to 32...Kb3.}) 34. Bxd8 Rxd8 35. Rc1+ (35. g6 Rc8 36. c7 b4 37. g7
b3) 35... Kb3 36. g6 Rc8 37. g7 a5 38. c7 a4 39. g4 $3 hxg4 40. Rb1+ Kc2 41.
